										<primary.official.content date.updated="0">
											<stat.subsect uuid="Iedac70302b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">This Code governs proceedings in the courts of
														Louisiana to the
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">extent and with the exceptions stated in Article
														1101.
													</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
										</primary.official.content>
										<primary.features date.updated="0">
											<official.commentary uuid="Iedb067d02b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" date.updated="0">
												<primary.head align="c" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold">LEGISLATIVE COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
													</name.block>
												</primary.head>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(a) This Article follows the pattern set by </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id297ac00241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="101">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence 101</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. The </t>
														<t style="para.text">provisions of this Code are largely modeled
															after the provisions of the Federal
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">Rules of Evidence of 1975.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(b) The provisions of this Code generally apply
															in both criminal and civil
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">proceedings. Generally hereafter, when a rule
															is designed and intended to apply
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">solely in criminal matters, the use of the word
															“accused” in the text will signify
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">its limited applicability or the rule will
															expressly state its limited applicability.
														</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
											</official.commentary>
											<editorial.commentary date.updated="0">
												<head align="c" toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.1">AUTHORS' COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</head>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="yes">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">This Article governs the scope of the Louisiana
															Code of Evi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">dence, which was enacted by the Louisiana
															Legislature in 1988.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">The Code of Evidence, which became effective on
															January 1, 1989,
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">is applicable to all civil and criminal
															proceedings in Louisiana
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">courts instituted on or after January 1, 1989.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">1</t>
														<xref id="1" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> When an Article </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">applies solely to criminal cases, the Article
															will use the word “ac
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">cused” or the Article will expressly state its
															limited applicability
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">to such cases.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">2</t>
														<xref id="2" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Although the adoption of the Louisiana Code of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">Evidence promotes the movement towards a
															uniform national
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">law of evidence, trial judges continue to have
															substantial discre
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">tion in many areas.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">3</t>
														<xref id="3" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> While patterned after the Federal Rules of </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">Evidence, the Louisiana Code of Evidence, in
															large part, codifies
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">and clarifies prior Louisiana law.</t>
													</para.text>
												</para>
											</editorial.commentary>
										</primary.features>
									</primary.section.body>
								</primary.section>
								<primary.section primary.section.type="article" uuid="I43473700d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" pgwidth="broad" date.revised="0" date.updated="0" element1="designator" prefix1="Art." suffix1=".">
									<sectionbreak sectionuuid="I45a396d0eac711d8b93285946e571caf"/><XPPMetaData uuid="I43473700d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" guid="I3ce3382202ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.uuid="I3ce3382202ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.dmsserial="296365682" md.first_line_cite="LAPRAC&amp;ndash;EVID ART. 102" md.pubpage="ART. 102" md.second_line_cite="La. Prac. Evidence Art. 102 (2017 ed.)" md.normalizedcite="LAPRAC-EVIDART.102" md.doc_family_uuid="I45a396d0eac711d8b93285946e571caf" md.third_line_cite="" md.pubid="165245" name="Art 102. Purpose and construction" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art
										102.
										Purpose and construction
									</XPPMetaData>
									<XPPHier uuid="I43473700d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" name="Art 102. Purpose and construction" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art 102.
										Purpose and construction
									</XPPHier>
									<primary.section.front date.updated="0">
										<primary.outline.name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0" all.align="l" all.designator.suffix="." all.label.suffix="." all.element.group="all" all.style="block" all.indent="0" all.capitalization="asis" all.name.block.font.size="11" all.date.updated="0">
											<label date.updated="0">
												<t style="label.1">Art</t>
											</label>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<designator date.updated="0">
												<t style="designator">102</t>
											</designator>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<primary.name date.updated="0">
												<name date.updated="0">
													<t style="name">Purpose and construction</t>
												</name>
												<t style="primary.name">
												</t>
											</primary.name>
										</primary.outline.name.block>
									</primary.section.front>
									<primary.section.body date.updated="0">
										<primary.official.content date.updated="0">
											<stat.subsect uuid="Iee30e2702b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">These articles shall be construed to secure
														fairness and effi
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">ciency in administration of the law of evidence
														to the end that
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">the truth may be ascertained and proceedings
														justly determined.
													</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
										</primary.official.content>
										<primary.features date.updated="0">
											<official.commentary uuid="Iee3353702b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" date.updated="0">
												<primary.head align="c" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold">LEGISLATIVE COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
													</name.block>
												</primary.head>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(a) This Article is a condensation of </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id29d0330241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="102">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence 102</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. It is </t>
														<t style="para.text">intended to particularize prior Louisiana law.
															The trial court continues to have
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">substantial discretion in many areas. On the
															other hand, the adoption of this
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="2" num-string="2" prev_page="1"/>
														<t style="para.text">Code facilitates the movement towards a uniform
															national law of evidence.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">Thus, especially where the language of the
															Louisiana Code is identical or virtu
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">ally identical with that used by other states
															or in the federal rules, Louisiana
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">courts now have available a body of persuasive
															authority which may be instruc
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">tive in interpreting the Louisiana Code.
															However, the federal rules have not
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">been followed slavishly, and Louisiana courts
															are by no means bound to follow
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">the precedents of these other courts.
															Furthermore, it is intended that the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">Articles be interpreted in light of their
															underlying spirit and that Louisiana
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">courts not be inexorably bound by prior
															interpretations of similar language in
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">pre-existing statutes. See </t>
														<cite>
															<ref ref.id="Id29d9f70241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="611" subref="(A)">
																<t style="ref">Art. 611(A)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(b) The rules and procedures embodied in the
															Articles of this Code do not rep
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">resent an attempt to interpret the Federal or
															Louisiana constitution.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">Constitutional questions should be resolved by
															the principles and rules of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">constitutional law. See generally </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="miscpub" ref.id="Id29dc680241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">G. Pugh, Louisiana Evidence Law, Ch. 5 (1974)
																</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1982154630" court="La." date="1982" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Ludwig" post.rptr="1073" pre.rptr="423" ref.id="Id29ded90241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Ludwig">
																<t style="ref">State v. Ludwig, 423 So. 2d 1073 (La. 1982)
																</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1983112842" court="La." date="1983" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Brown" post.rptr="438" pre.rptr="428" ref.id="Id29e14a0241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Brown">
																<t style="ref">State v. Brown, 428 So. 2d 438 (La. </t>
																<t style="ref">1983)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1983149956" court="La." date="1983" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Vaughn" post.rptr="1260" pre.rptr="448" ref.id="Id29fc250241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Vaughn">
																<t style="ref">State v. Vaughn, 448 So. 2d 1260 (La. 1983)
																</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text"> (overruled by, State v. </t>
															<t style="para.text">Johnson, 664 So. 2d 94 (La. 1995)</t>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. In criminal matters especially the Articles
															of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">this Code must be interpreted and applied in
															light of and within the confines
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">mandated by the Louisiana and federal
															constitutions. See
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref amendref="IV" normalpub="statute-us-const" ref.id="Id2a19710241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">U.S. Const. Amends. </t>
																<t style="ref">IV</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref amendref="V" normalpub="statute-us-const" ref.id="Id2a19711241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">V</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref amendref="VI" normalpub="statute-us-const" ref.id="Id2a1be20241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">VI</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">, &amp; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref amendref="IV" normalpub="statute-us-const" ref.id="Id2a1e530241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">XIV</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="I" date="1974" normalpub="statute-us-la-const" ref.id="Id2a20c40241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="2">
																<t style="ref">La. Const. Art. I, </t>
																<t style="ref cgt">§§ </t>
																<t style="ref">2</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref artref="I" date="1974" normalpub="statute-us-la-const" ref.id="Id2a20c41241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="3">
																<t style="ref">3</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref artref="I" date="1974" normalpub="statute-us-la-const" ref.id="Id2a20c42241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="5">
																<t style="ref">5</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref artref="I" date="1974" normalpub="statute-us-la-const" rangeend="to 19" rangetype="secref" ref.id="Id2a47d40241411e68b798696bfab1886" secrange="y" secref="13">
																<t style="ref">13 to 19 (1974)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. Louisiana has </t>
														<t style="para.text">developed a firm tradition of commitment to the
															scrupulous observance of the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">basic tenets of fair play inherent in the
															constitutional safeguards of due process.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">See, e.g., </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1983112842" court="La." date="1983" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Brown" post.rptr="438" pre.rptr="428" ref.id="Id2a4cb60241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Brown">
																<t style="ref">State v. Brown, 428 So. 2d 438 (La. 1983)</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text"> (overruled by, State v. </t>
															<t style="para.text">Johnson, 664 So. 2d 94 (La. 1995)</t>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1983134072" court="La." date="1983" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Kahey" post.rptr="475" pre.rptr="436" ref.id="Id2a51980241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Kahey">
																<t style="ref">State v. Kahey, 436 So. 2d 475 (La. 1983)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1983127399" court="La." date="1983" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Square" post.rptr="104" pre.rptr="433" ref.id="Id2a54090241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Square">
																<t style="ref">State v. Square, 433 So. 2d 104 (La. 1983)
																</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. In various particulars the Louisiana </t>
														<t style="para.text">Constitution of 1974 goes further than its
															federal counterpart in protecting the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">interests of the accused and the general
															citizenry against governmental and
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">private abuses, intrusions, and improprieties.
															Compare
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="I" date="1974" normalpub="statute-us-la-const" ref.id="Id2a567a0241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">La. Const. Art. I (1974)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">(Declaration of Rights) with </t>
														<cite>
															<ref amendrange="y" amendref="1" normalpub="statute-us-const" rangeend="to 10" rangetype="amendref" ref.id="Id2a84dd0241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">U.S. Const. Amends. 1 to 10</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> (Bill of Rights). No </t>
														<t style="para.text">intent to alter or delimit these safeguards and
															principles is intended, nor would
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">any such attempt or effect be constitutionally
															permissible.
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="VI" normalpub="statute-us-const" ref.id="Id2a874e0241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">U.S. Const. Art. VI</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. </t>
														<t style="para.text">Under special factual circumstances certain
															specific and otherwise mandatory
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">provisions of this Code must necessarily bow to
															these notions of fundamental
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">fairness. See, e.g., </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1973126337" date="1973" fjur="Sup Ct" jur="US" norm.rptr="us" p1="Chambers" p2="Mississippi" post.rptr="284" pre.rptr="410" ref.id="Id2a89bf0241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="Chambers v. Mississippi">
																<t style="ref">Chambers v. Mississippi, 410 U.S. 284, 93 S.
																	Ct. 1038, 35 L.
																</t>
																<t style="ref">Ed. 2d 297 (1973)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1974127137" date="1974" fjur="Sup Ct" jur="US" norm.rptr="us" p1="Davis" p2="Alaska" post.rptr="308" pre.rptr="415" ref.id="Id2a8c300241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="Davis v. Alaska">
																<t style="ref">Davis v. Alaska, 415 U.S. 308, 94 S. Ct.
																	1105, 39 L. Ed. 2d
																</t>
																<t style="ref">347 (1974)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1983149956" court="La." date="1983" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Vaughn" post.rptr="1260" pre.rptr="448" ref.id="Id2ab0cf0241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Vaughn">
																<t style="ref">State v. Vaughn, 448 So. 2d 1260 (La. 1983)
																</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. The constitutional in</t>
														<t style="para.text">terpretation and application of this Code in
															these circumstances is entrusted to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">the judiciary.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
											</official.commentary>
											<editorial.commentary date.updated="0">
												<head align="c" toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.1">AUTHORS' COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</head>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="yes">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">This Article addresses how the articles
															contained in the Louisi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ana Code of Evidence are to be construed which
															is to secure fair
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ness and efficiency in administration of the
															law of evidence to the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">end that the truth may be ascertained and
															proceedings justly
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">determined. In construing the Code of Evidence,
															trial judges
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">should feel free to exercise their considerable
															discretion in order
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">to achieve the objectives contained in Article
															102.
														</t>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">In </t>
														<t style="ital">State v. Rosales</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">, the court used Article 102 to hold that the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">defendant, a non-native speaker of English, was
															not denied his
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">fundamental right to a sworn-in interpreter
															because the defen
														</t>
														<t style="dt">-</t>
														<pagebreak num="3" num-string="3" prev_page="2"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">dant could understand and express himself in
															English.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">1</t>
														<xref id="4" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> On ap</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">peal of his conviction for driving while
															intoxicated (DWI), third
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">offense, the defendant argued that the trial
															court erred in deny
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ing his motion to quash predicate offense
															number one where, he,
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">a non-native speaker, was denied his
															fundamental right to a
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">sworn-in interpreter, resulting in a violation
															of his
														</t>
														<t style="ital">Boykin</t>
														<t style="para.text.1"> rights.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">2</t>
														<xref id="5" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">The court held that a defendant who understands
															the English
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">language renders an interpreter gratuitous as
															the interpreter
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">cannot assist the judge in understanding the
															evidence or to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">determine a fact at issue.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">3</t>
														<xref id="6" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Consequently, requiring an interpreter </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">for an English-speaking defendant would be the
															height of ineffi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ciency, something that Article 102 is designed
															to eliminate.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">4</t>
														<xref id="7" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
											</editorial.commentary>
										</primary.features>
									</primary.section.body>
								</primary.section>
								<primary.section primary.section.type="article" uuid="I435a22c0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" pgwidth="broad" date.revised="0" date.updated="0" element1="designator" prefix1="Art." suffix1=".">
									<sectionbreak sectionuuid="I45a396d1eac711d8b93285946e571caf"/><XPPMetaData uuid="I435a22c0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" guid="I3ce3382502ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.uuid="I3ce3382502ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.dmsserial="296365705" md.first_line_cite="LAPRAC&amp;ndash;EVID ART. 103" md.pubpage="ART. 103" md.second_line_cite="La. Prac. Evidence Art. 103 (2017 ed.)" md.normalizedcite="LAPRAC-EVIDART.103" md.doc_family_uuid="I45a396d1eac711d8b93285946e571caf" md.third_line_cite="" md.pubid="165245" name="Art 103. Rulings on evidence" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art 103.
										Rulings on evidence
									</XPPMetaData>
									<XPPHier uuid="I435a22c0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" name="Art 103. Rulings on evidence" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art 103.
										Rulings on evidence
									</XPPHier>
									<primary.section.front date.updated="0">
										<primary.outline.name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0" all.align="l" all.designator.suffix="." all.label.suffix="." all.element.group="all" all.style="block" all.indent="0" all.capitalization="asis" all.name.block.font.size="11" all.date.updated="0">
											<label date.updated="0">
												<t style="label.1">Art</t>
											</label>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<designator date.updated="0">
												<t style="designator">103</t>
											</designator>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<primary.name date.updated="0">
												<name date.updated="0">
													<t style="name">Rulings on evidence</t>
												</name>
												<t style="primary.name">
												</t>
											</primary.name>
										</primary.outline.name.block>
									</primary.section.front>
									<primary.section.body date.updated="0">
										<primary.official.content date.updated="0">
											<stat.subsect uuid="Iee7b31e02b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<designator date.updated="0">
															<t style="designator.2">A.</t>
														</designator>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.2">Effect of erroneous ruling.</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</stat.name.block>
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">Error may not be predicated </t>
													<t style="stat.text">upon a ruling which admits or excludes evidence
														unless a
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">substantial right of the party is affected, and
													</t>
												</stat.text>
												<stat.para uuid="Iee7c91702b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0" first.para="yes">
													<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
														<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
															<designator date.updated="0">
																<t style="designator.2">(1)</t>
															</designator>
															<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
															</t>
															<name date.updated="0">
																<t style="bold.2">Ruling admitting evidence.</t>
															</name>
															<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
															</t>
														</name.block>
													</stat.name.block>
													<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="stat.text">When the ruling is one </t>
														<t style="stat.text">admitting evidence, a timely objection or
															motion to admonish
														</t>
														<t style="stat.text">the jury to limit or disregard appears of
															record, stating the
														</t>
														<t style="stat.text">specific ground of objection; or</t>
													</stat.text>
												</stat.para>
												<stat.para uuid="Iee8432902b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
														<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
															<designator date.updated="0">
																<t style="designator.2">(2)</t>
															</designator>
															<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
															</t>
															<name date.updated="0">
																<t style="bold.2">Ruling excluding evidence.</t>
															</name>
															<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
															</t>
														</name.block>
													</stat.name.block>
													<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="stat.text">When the ruling is one </t>
														<t style="stat.text">excluding evidence, the substance of the
															evidence was made
														</t>
														<t style="stat.text">known to the court by counsel.</t>
													</stat.text>
												</stat.para>
											</stat.subsect>
											<stat.subsect uuid="Iee8655702b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<designator date.updated="0">
															<t style="designator.2">B.</t>
														</designator>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.2">Record of ruling.</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</stat.name.block>
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">The court may add any other or further </t>
													<t style="stat.text">statement which shows the character of the
														evidence, the form in
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">which it was offered, the objection made, and
														the ruling thereon.
													</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
											<stat.subsect uuid="Iee8718c02b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<designator date.updated="0">
															<t style="designator.2">C.</t>
														</designator>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.2">Hearing of jury.</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</stat.name.block>
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">In jury cases, proceedings shall be </t>
													<t style="stat.text">conducted, to the extent practicable, so as to
														prevent inadmis
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">sible evidence from being suggested to the jury
														by any means,
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">such as making statements or asking questions in
														the hearing of
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">the jury.</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
										</primary.official.content>
										<primary.features date.updated="0">
											<official.commentary uuid="Iee8914902b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" date.updated="0">
												<primary.head align="c" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold">LEGISLATIVE COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
													</name.block>
												</primary.head>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(a) Paragraph A of this Article generally
															follows
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2ae6850241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="103" subref="(a)">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence </t>
																<t style="ref">103(a)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">, but as a result of Senate Committee
															amendments is more exacting than
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">its Federal Rules counterpart. It continues the
															general requirement in Louisi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">ana law that there be a contemporaneous
															objection.
														</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(b) Paragraph B of this Article generally
															follows
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2ae8f60241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="103" subref="(b)">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence </t>
																<pagebreak num="4" num-string="4" prev_page="3"/>
																<t style="ref">103(b)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">, and is not intended to change Louisiana law.
															It simply clarifies the prior
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">practice of trial judges' offering brief “per
															curiam” explanations regarding the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">admission or exclusion of evidence. See </t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="17" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcrimp" ref.id="Id2b0d950241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">La. C.Cr.P. Arts. 17</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref artref="844" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcrimp" ref.id="Id2b10060241411e68b798696bfab1886" subref="(D)">
																<t style="ref">844(D)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="1631" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcivp" ref.id="Id2b12770241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">La. C.C.P. </t>
																<t style="ref">Arts. 1631</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref artref="1636" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcivp" ref.id="Id2b12771241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">1636</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(c) Paragraph C of this Article generally
															follows
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2b14e80241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="103" subref="(c)">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence </t>
																<t style="ref">103(c)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> and is not intended to change prior law. See
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="794" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcrimp" ref.id="Id2b17590241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">La. C.Cr.P. Art. 794</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. </t>
														<t style="para.text">Implementation of the rule is left to the broad
															discretion of the trial judge. See
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref ref.id="Id2b3bf80241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="611" subref="(A)">
																<t style="ref">Art. 611(A)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
											</official.commentary>
											<editorial.commentary date.updated="0">
												<head align="c" toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.1">AUTHORS' COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</head>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="yes">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Subparagraph A(1) of this Article preserves the
															contemporane
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ous objection rule relative to rulings
															admitting evidence.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">1</t>
														<xref id="8" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Under </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">this rule, to preserve the right to appeal an
															erroneous trial court
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ruling related to the admission of evidence,
															the objecting party
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">must make a timely and specific objection.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">2</t>
														<xref id="9" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> The objecting party </t>
														<pagebreak num="5" num-string="5" prev_page="4"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">should, at the time the ruling is made, make
															known to the trial
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">court his objections and the specific grounds
															therefor. In criminal
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">cases, Article 103 and </t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="841" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcivp" ref.id="Id2bbfce0241411e68b798696bfab1886" subref="(A)">
																<t style="ref.2">C.C.P. art. 841(A)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text.1"> are designed to promote </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">judicial efficiency by preventing a criminal
															defendant from
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">gambling on a favorable verdict and, then, upon
															conviction, as
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">serting on appeal errors which either could
															have been avoided or
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">corrected at the time or should have put an
															immediate halt to the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proceedings.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">3</t>
														<xref id="10" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> This informs the court and the opponent of the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">basis of the objection. Moreover, a new basis
															for an objection may
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">not be urged for the first time on appeal.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">4</t>
														<xref id="11" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> When the alleged er</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">roneous evidence has been heard by the jury,
															the objecting party
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">should move to strike the evidence from the
															record and request
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">that the judge admonish the jury not to
															consider such evidence.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">5</t>
														<xref id="12" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">If a timely and specific objection is not made
															to a ruling admit
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ting evidence, the objection is waived and
															cannot be raised on
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">appeal.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">6</t>
														<xref id="13" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Further, under the Article, error may not be
															successfully
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">raised on appeal unless a substantial right of
															the party is
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="6" num-string="6" prev_page="5"/>
														<pagebreak num="7" num-string="7" prev_page="6"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">affected.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">7</t>
														<xref id="14" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> When determining whether a substantial right
															of the
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="8" num-string="8" prev_page="7"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">party has been affected, the court considers
															whether the alleged
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">error as compared to the entire record had a
															substantial effect on
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the outcome of the case.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">8</t>
														<xref id="15" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<pagebreak num="9" num-string="9" prev_page="8"/>
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Under prior law, the contemporaneous objection
															rule did not
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">apply in capital cases; in capital cases, all
															assignments of error
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">are reviewed by the appellate court.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">9</t>
														<xref id="16" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Presumably, this rule applies under the
															Louisiana Code of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">Evidence.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">10</t>
														<xref id="17" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> The contemporaneous objection rule also
															applies to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">prosecutorial misconduct. Thus, if a criminal
															defendant fails to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">contemporaneously object at trial to the
															prosecutor's alleged
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">conduct, the defendant has waived any error
															based on these
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">allegations.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">11</t>
														<xref id="18" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Subparagraph A(2) of the Article governs offers
															of proof or
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proffers. When a trial court sustains an
															objection excluding evi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">dence, the proponent should then make an offer
															of proof in order
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">to preserve the trial record for the appellate
															court to review.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">12</t>
														<xref id="19" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">The offer of proof may also persuade the trial
															judge to change his
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ruling. Under Subparagraph A(2), “in criminal
															cases as well as
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">civil cases, a party now has a legal right,
															when evidence has been
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">excluded, to make an offer of proof of what
															counsel expects to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">prove, outside the presence of the jury.”</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">13</t>
														<xref id="20" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">An offer of proof is simply an offer of the
															evidence that is being
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">excluded. The purpose of an offer of proof is
															to create a record of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the excluded evidence so that the reviewing
															court will know what
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the evidence was and will thus be able to
															determine if the exclu
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">sion was improper and, if so, whether the
															improper exclusion
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">constituted reversible error.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">14</t>
														<xref id="21" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> The offer of proof also informs the </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">trial court and the opposing party of the
															substance of the excluded
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">evidence. In order to preserve the right to
															appeal a trial court
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ruling that excludes evidence, the party must
															make the substance
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">of the evidence known to the trial court.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">15</t>
														<xref id="22" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Furthermore, error </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">may not be successfully raised on appeal unless
															a substantial
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="10" num-string="10" prev_page="9"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">right of the party is affected.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">16</t>
														<xref id="23" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> If the proponent of the excluded </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">evidence either fails to request an opportunity
															to make an offer of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proof or to make a proffer at the trial, he
															cannot contend on ap
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">peal that such exclusion was erroneous.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">17</t>
														<xref id="24" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> When a request for a </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proffer of evidence is made, the proponent of
															the evidence must
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">make the proffer as directed by the trial
															judge. Thus, when the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">trial judge states that the proffer of evidence
															must be made after
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the completion of the trial, the proffering
															party is responsible for
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ensuring that the proffer of evidence is made.
															If the proffer of ev
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">idence is not made, there will be no evidence
															for the court of ap
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">peal to review and the action of the trial
															court will not be in
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">error.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">18</t>
														<xref id="25" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> In proffering evidence, the offering party
															may: (1) make a
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">complete record of the proffered testimony or
															(2) present a state
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ment describing what he expects to prove by the
															proffered
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">evidence.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">19</t>
														<xref id="26" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> In other words, when making an offer of proof,
															the of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">fering party can either make a narrative
															statement of the prof
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">fered evidence on the record, or it can present
															the evidence in
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">question and answer form by calling the witness
															to the stand and
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">asking him questions. The witness is then
															subject to cross-
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="11" num-string="11" prev_page="10"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">examination. In each instance, the offer of
															proof should be made
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">out of the jury's presence.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">20</t>
														<xref id="27" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> The trial judge has discretion as to </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">what type of proffer is allowed.</t>
													</para.text>
												</para>
											</editorial.commentary>
										</primary.features>
									</primary.section.body>
								</primary.section>
								<primary.section primary.section.type="article" uuid="I438db5e0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" pgwidth="broad" date.revised="0" date.updated="0" element1="designator" prefix1="Art." suffix1=".">
									<sectionbreak sectionuuid="I45a3bde0eac711d8b93285946e571caf"/><XPPMetaData uuid="I438db5e0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" guid="I3ce3382802ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.uuid="I3ce3382802ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.dmsserial="296365732" md.first_line_cite="LAPRAC&amp;ndash;EVID ART. 104" md.pubpage="ART. 104" md.second_line_cite="La. Prac. Evidence Art. 104 (2017 ed.)" md.normalizedcite="LAPRAC-EVIDART.104" md.doc_family_uuid="I45a3bde0eac711d8b93285946e571caf" md.third_line_cite="" md.pubid="165245" name="Art 104. Preliminary questions" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art
										104.
										Preliminary questions
									</XPPMetaData>
									<XPPHier uuid="I438db5e0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" name="Art 104. Preliminary questions" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art 104.
										Preliminary questions
									</XPPHier>
									<primary.section.front date.updated="0">
										<primary.outline.name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0" all.align="l" all.designator.suffix="." all.label.suffix="." all.element.group="all" all.style="block" all.indent="0" all.capitalization="asis" all.name.block.font.size="11" all.date.updated="0">
											<label date.updated="0">
												<t style="label.1">Art</t>
											</label>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<designator date.updated="0">
												<t style="designator">104</t>
											</designator>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<primary.name date.updated="0">
												<name date.updated="0">
													<t style="name">Preliminary questions</t>
												</name>
												<t style="primary.name">
												</t>
											</primary.name>
										</primary.outline.name.block>
									</primary.section.front>
									<primary.section.body date.updated="0">
										<primary.official.content date.updated="0">
											<stat.subsect uuid="Ief4d9d102b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<designator date.updated="0">
															<t style="designator.2">A.</t>
														</designator>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.2">Questions of admissibility generally.</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</stat.name.block>
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">Preliminary ques</t>
													<t style="stat.text">tions concerning the competency or qualification
														of a person to be
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">a witness, the existence of a privilege, or the
														admissibility of evi
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">dence shall be determined by the court, subject
														to the provisions
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">of Paragraph B. In making its determination, it
														is not bound by
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">the rules of evidence except those with respect
														to privileges.
													</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
											<stat.subsect uuid="Ief4e39502b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<designator date.updated="0">
															<t style="designator.2">B.</t>
														</designator>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.2">Relevancy conditioned on fact.</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</stat.name.block>
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">Subject to other provi</t>
													<t style="stat.text">sions of this Code, when the relevancy of
														evidence depends upon
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">the fulfillment of a condition of fact, the
														court shall admit it
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">upon, or subject to, the introduction of
														evidence sufficient to sup
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">port a finding of the fulfillment of the
														condition.
													</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
											<stat.subsect uuid="Ief4ed5902b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<designator date.updated="0">
															<t style="designator.2">C.</t>
														</designator>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.2">Hearing of jury.</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</stat.name.block>
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">Hearings on matters to be decided by the </t>
													<t style="stat.text">judge alone shall be conducted out of the
														hearing of the jury
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">when the interests of justice require. Hearings
														on the admissibil
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">ity of confessions or admissions by the accused
														or evidence alleg
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">edly unlawfully obtained shall in all cases be
														conducted out of the
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">hearing of the jury, but when there has been a
														ruling prior to
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">trial, it shall not be necessary to conduct
														another hearing as to
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">admissibility before presentation of the
														evidence to a jury.
													</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
											<stat.subsect uuid="Ief5083402b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.name.block date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<designator date.updated="0">
															<t style="designator.2">D.</t>
														</designator>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.2">Weight and credibility.</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block.1 cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</stat.name.block>
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">The preliminary determination by </t>
													<t style="stat.text">the court that evidence is admissible does not
														limit the right of a
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">party to introduce evidence relevant to weight
														or credibility at
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">the trial.</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
										</primary.official.content>
										<primary.features date.updated="0">
											<official.commentary uuid="Ief527f102b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" date.updated="0">
												<primary.head align="c" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold">LEGISLATIVE COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
													</name.block>
												</primary.head>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(a) Paragraph A of this Article is based
															substantially on
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2e508b0241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="104" subref="(a)">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evi</t>
																<t style="ref">dence 104(a)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. Unlike the federal model, this Article
															distinguishes between wit
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">ness competency and witness qualification. See
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref commentref="(c)" ref.id="Id2e52fc0241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="601">
																<t style="ref">Art. 601, comment (c)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref ref.id="Id2e52fc1241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="605">
																<t style="ref">Art. 605</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref commentref="(a)" ref.id="Id2e52fc2241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="606">
																<t style="ref">Art. 606, comment (a)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. The Paragraph is intended to clarify and
															particularize,
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">but not to change, prior Louisiana law. See,
															e.g., former La. R.S. 15:466;
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1982147746" court="La." date="1982" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Michel" post.rptr="1115" pre.rptr="422" ref.id="Id2e556d0241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Michel">
																<t style="ref">State </t>
																<t style="ref">v. Michel, 422 So. 2d 1115 (La. 1982)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1911000589" date="1911" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="la" p1="State" p2="Lee" post.rptr="1077" pre.rptr="127" ref.id="Id2e556d1241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Lee">
																<t style="ref">State v. Lee, 127 La. 1077, 54 So. 356 </t>
																<t style="ref">(1911)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(b) Distinguishing between the situations to
															which Paragraphs A and B of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">this Article are applicable can be difficult.
															In general, when the law expressly
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">requires the satisfaction of a factual
															precondition to the admissibility of evi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">dence, as for example with all of the hearsay
															exceptions and the rule on admis
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">sibility of co-conspirators' statements,
															Paragraph A requires the judge alone to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">determine whether the precondition is
															satisfied. The contrary approach of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">Paragraph B applies in those comparatively
															infrequent situations where an
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">objection is based on conditional relevancy. In
															Paragraph B situations the judge
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">decides admissibility by a lesser standard than
															in those governed by Paragraph
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">A, and the jury undertakes the ultimate
															decision as to probative value.
														</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<pagebreak num="12" num-string="12" prev_page="11"/>
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(c) In making the determinations called for by
															Paragraph A the trial judge
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">should generally apply the preponderance of
															evidence standard. McCormick
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">states that this is “[t]he most commonly
															accepted standard” (
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref author="C. McCormick" date="1984" normalpub="mccorev3" noteref="8" pageref="136" ref.id="Id2e68f50241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="53">
																<t style="ref">C. McCormick, On </t>
																<t style="ref">Evidence </t>
																<t style="ref cgt">§ </t>
																<t style="ref">53, at 136 n.8 (3d ed. 1984)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">) and has generally not given the courts </t>
														<t style="para.text">difficulty. If, of course, the law prescribes a
															particular foundation or sets forth
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">other special prerequisites for the
															admissibility of evidence, those requirements
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">must be met. See, e.g., </t>
														<cite>
															<ref ref.id="Id2e6b660241411e68b798696bfab1886" secrange="y" secref="602 and 901 et seq.">
																<t style="ref">Arts. 602 and 901 et seq.</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> (sufficient to support a finding); </t>
														<t style="para.text">Art. 1103, </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1973134140" court="La." date="1973" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Prieur" post.rptr="126" pre.rptr="277" ref.id="Id2e70480241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Prieur">
																<t style="ref">State v. Prieur, 277 So. 2d 126 (La. 1973)
																</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">and </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1984120230" court="La." date="1984" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Davis" post.rptr="466" pre.rptr="449" ref.id="Id2e70481241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Davis">
																<t style="ref">State v. Davis, 449 So. </t>
																<t style="ref">2d 466 (La. 1984)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> (clear and convincing evidence of other
															criminal acts);
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="statute-us-la-revstat" ref.id="Id2e752a0241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="15:451">
																<t style="ref">La. </t>
																<t style="ref">R.S. 15:451</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> (requirement for admission of confessions);
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1983127381" court="La." date="1983" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="State" p2="Neslo" post.rptr="73" pre.rptr="433" ref.id="Id2e779b0241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Neslo">
																<t style="ref">State v. Neslo, 433 So. </t>
																<t style="ref">2d 73 (La. 1983)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> (proof beyond a reasonable doubt of
															voluntariness required);
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">Art. 801(D)(3)(b) (coconspirator's statements;
															prima facie standard).
														</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(d) The final sentence of Paragraph A is based
															on the recognition that most of
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">the rules of evidence are intended to regulate
															the quality and reliability of evi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">dence reaching the untrained juror, not the
															court. Privileged matters receive
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">special treatment, however, due to the interest
															in and need for confidentiality
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">as to them. This provision supersedes decisions
															such as
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1982155093" court="La. Ct. App. 1st Cir." date="1982" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="Matter of Succession of Martin" p1.pp="Matter of" post.rptr="1219" pre.rptr="424" ref.id="Id2e7c7d0241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="Matter of Succession of Martin">
																<t style="ref">Matter of Succession of </t>
																<t style="ref">Martin, 424 So. 2d 1219 (La. Ct. App. 1st
																	Cir. 1982)
																</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">, which held that a trial </t>
														<t style="para.text">court may not consider hearsay in determining
															whether a declarant is unavail
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">able for purposes of the hearsay rule. Other
															examples of preliminary determina
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">tions to which this sentence applies include
															whether the foundation of Article
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">608(A)(2) has been established or whether a
															hearsay declarant was sufficiently
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">excited under Article 803(2). Although as to
															preliminary matters the judge is
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">not normally bound by the rules of evidence,
															the record must reflect the basis
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">for the court's decision. As regards claims of
															privilege, since
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="1422" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcivp" ref.id="Id2e83d00241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">Article 1422 of the </t>
																<t style="ref">La. Code of Civil Procedure</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> exempts privileged matters from discovery, in
															some
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">cases the trial judge may be called upon to
															decide the existence of a privilege
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">prior to trial rather than during it. The issue
															may also arise in pretrial discus
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">sions in criminal matters.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(e) Paragraph B of this Article is based on </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2e83d01241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="104" subref="(b)">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence 104(b)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. It </t>
														<t style="para.text">is intended to clarify prior Louisiana law. See
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1933127688" court="La. Ct. App. 2d Cir." date="1933" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so" p1="Kinnison" p2="Wall" post.rptr="371" pre.rptr="146" ref.id="Id2e83d02241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="Kinnison v. Wall">
																<t style="ref">Kinnison v. Wall, 146 So. 371 (La. </t>
																<t style="ref">Ct. App. 2d Cir. 1933)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1943121329" court="La. Ct. App. 1st Cir." date="1942" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="Camden Fire Ins. Ass'n" p2="Fontenot" post.rptr="99" pre.rptr="11" ref.id="Id2e90050241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="Camden Fire Ins. Ass'n v. Fontenot">
																<t style="ref">Camden Fire Ins. Ass'n v. Fontenot, 11 So. 2d
																	99 (La. Ct.
																</t>
																<t style="ref">App. 1st Cir. 1942)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. This provision does not affect preconditions
															to admissibility
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">imposed by particularized rules that are not
															concerned with conditional
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">relevancy. See, e.g., </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="statute-us-la-revstat" ref.id="Id2e90051241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="15:451">
																<t style="ref">La. R.S. 15:451</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> (free and voluntary confessions); </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1959128308" date="1959" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="la" p1="State" p2="Brown" post.rptr="562" pre.rptr="236" ref.id="Id2e97580241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="State v. Brown">
																<t style="ref">State v. </t>
																<t style="ref">Brown, 236 La. 562, 108 So. 2d 233 (1959)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text"> (corpus delicti).</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(f) The phrase “evidence sufficient to support
															a finding” in Paragraph B is also
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">used in Articles 602 and 901. It suggests that
															the trial court should admit the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">conditionally relevant evidence if the
															preliminary evidence of the condition is
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">such that a rational juror could conclude that
															the condition exists fulfilled.
														</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(g) Paragraph C of this Article is based on </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2e97581241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="104" subref="(c)">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence 104(c)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. It </t>
														<t style="para.text">includes language originally submitted by the
															United States Supreme Court's
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">Advisory Committee mandating that motions to
															suppress evidence be conducted
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">out of the hearing of the jury. That additional
															language was inexplicably deleted
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">from the final federal source provision. See
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="miscpub" ref.id="Id2ea86f0241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">1 J. Weinstein &amp; M. Berger, </t>
																<t style="ref">Weinstein's Evidence </t>
																<t style="ref cgt">¶ </t>
																<t style="ref">104[10] (1982)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. It does not change Louisiana law. See </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="statute-us-la-revstat" ref.id="Id2eaae00241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="15:451">
																<t style="ref">La. R.S. 15:451</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="703" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcrimp" ref.id="Id2eaae01241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">La. C.Cr.P. Arts. 703</t>
															</ref>
															<t style="para.text">, </t>
															<ref artref="794" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcrimp" ref.id="Id2eaae02241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">794</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. As in the federal model, in this </t>
														<t style="para.text">Paragraph and in Article 103(C), no attempt has
															been made to detail what
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">other matters should be heard out of the
															hearing of the jury, except for the al
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">leged confessions and admissions of accuseds.
															See
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref ref.id="Id2eb9860241411e68b798696bfab1886" secref="104" subref="(A)">
																<t style="ref">Art. 104(A)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1964124873" date="1964" fjur="Sup Ct" jur="US" norm.rptr="us" p1="Jackson" p2="Denno" post.rptr="368" pre.rptr="378" ref.id="Id2ebbf70241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="Jackson v. Denno">
																<t style="ref">Jackson v. Denno, </t>
																<t style="ref">378 U.S. 368, 84 S. Ct. 1774, 12 L. Ed. 2d
																	908 (1964)
																</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">; </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="miscpub" ref.id="Id2ebbf71241411e68b798696bfab1886">
																<t style="ref">1 J. Weinstein &amp; M. </t>
																<t style="ref">Berger, Weinstein's Evidence </t>
																<t style="ref cgt">¶ </t>
																<t style="ref">104[07] (1982)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">(h) Paragraph D of this Article is based
															substantially on
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2ebe680241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="104" subref="(e)">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evi</t>
																<t style="ref">dence 104(e)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. It is not intended to change prior Louisiana
															law. See former La.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">R.S. 15:462. The use of the phrase “at the
															trial” instead of “before the jury,”
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">which is used in the federal rule, makes clear
															that this rule is applicable in both
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="13" num-string="13" prev_page="12"/>
														<t style="para.text">jury and bench trials.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
											</official.commentary>
											<editorial.commentary date.updated="0">
												<head align="c" toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.1">AUTHORS' COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</head>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="yes">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">At a trial, the judge has the power to regulate
															and control the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proceedings in his court. As to factual or
															legal determinations
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">during a trial, the judge will determine
															questions of law while
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the jury will determine questions of fact.</t>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">However, a number of issues such as the
															competency or qualifi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">cation of a person to be a witness,</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">1</t>
														<xref id="28" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> the existence of a privilege,</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">2</t>
														<xref id="29" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">and the admissibility of evidence often depend
															on the determina
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">tion of certain preliminary factual questions
															that may be in
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">dispute. Under Article 104(A), which is based
															substantially on
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2ec34a0241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="104" subref="(a)">
																<t style="ref.2">Federal Rule of Evidence 104(a)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text.1">, these preliminary questions of </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">fact shall be determined by the trial judge. In
															making these
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">determinations, the judge should apply the
															preponderance of the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">evidence standard unless the law prescribes a
															particular founda
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">tion or sets forth other special prerequisites
															for the admissibility
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">of evidence.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">3</t>
														<xref id="30" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Except for privilege questions, the judge is
															not bound
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">by the rules of evidence in making his
															determination.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">4</t>
														<xref id="31" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> This is </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">based on the recognition that most of the rules
															of evidence are
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">intended to regulate the quality and
															reliability of evidence reach
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ing the untrained juror, not the judge.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">5</t>
														<xref id="32" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> For example, in determin</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ing whether a hearsay statement by a declarant
															falls under the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">present sense impression exception to the
															hearsay rule, the judge
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">may consider evidence that is inadmissible at
															the trial. Even
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">though as to preliminary matters the judge is
															not normally bound
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="14" num-string="14" prev_page="13"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">by the rules of evidence, the record must
															reflect the basis for the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">court's decision.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">6</t>
														<xref id="33" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Hearings on preliminary matters that must be
															determined by
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the trial judge under this Article should
															generally be conducted
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">out of the hearing of the jury.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">7</t>
														<xref id="34" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> The purpose of this requirement is </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">to prevent the jury from being prejudiced by
															hearing evidence
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">that may later be ruled inadmissible. The judge
															has great discre
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">tion as to which matters should be determined
															within the hear
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ing of the jury. However, hearings on the
															voluntariness of a
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">confession or admission by the accused or
															evidence allegedly
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">unlawfully obtained should always be conducted
															out of the hear
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ing of the jury.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">8</t>
														<xref id="35" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> It should also be noted that the judge may </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">determine many preliminary matters at pre-trial
															hearings. When
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">this occurs, it is not necessary for the judge
															to conduct additional
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">hearings on the matters before the presentation
															of the evidence
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">to the jury.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">9</t>
														<xref id="36" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Finally, the preliminary determination by a
															trial
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">judge that evidence is admissible does not
															limit the right of a
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">party to introduce evidence relevant to weight
															or credibility at
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">trial.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">10</t>
														<xref id="37" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Sometimes the relevancy of a particular item of
															evidence
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">depends on the fulfillment of a related
															condition of fact. This sit
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">uation is known as conditional relevancy and is
															governed by
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">Paragraph B of the Article. Under Paragraph B,
															it is the jury, not
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the judge, who determines issues of conditional
															relevance. The
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">judge has the discretion to admit conditionally
															relevant evidence
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">“upon, or subject to, the introduction of
															evidence sufficient to sup
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">port a finding of the fulfillment of the
															condition.” This means that
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the judge could admit the conditionally
															relevant evidence prior
														</t>
														<pagebreak num="15" num-string="15" prev_page="14"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">to, or after, the introduction of sufficient
															evidence such that a
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">reasonable jury could find that the condition
															was met. For
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">example, when a spoken statement is relied upon
															to prove notice
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">to X, the statement has no relevance to the
															case unless it is
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proven that X heard the statement.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">11</t>
														<xref id="38" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> If the judge admits the </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">conditionally relevant evidence prior to the
															introduction of the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">preliminary evidence sufficient to fulfill the
															condition, the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proponent of the evidence then has a duty to
															“connect up” or “link
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">up” the conditionally relevant evidence at a
															later time. When the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">proponent proceeds to link up the conditionally
															relevant evidence,
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the jury, as the finder of fact, then
															determines whether the condi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">tion has been met. If after all the evidence is
															in on the issue, and
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the judge determines that a reasonable jury
															could determine that
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the condition was established, the issue is for
															them. On the other
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">hand, if the judge determines that the evidence
															is not such as to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">allow a finding of the condition, after a
															motion to strike by the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">opponent of the evidence, the judge should
															withdraw the prelimi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">nary evidence from the jury's consideration and
															instruct the jury
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">to disregard the evidence.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">12</t>
														<xref id="39" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> In the example above, if the spoken </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">statement is introduced subject to the
															introduction of evidence
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">that X heard the statement and such evidence is
															not produced,
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the judge should withdraw the spoken statement
															from the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">consideration of the jury and instruct the jury
															not to consider the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">spoken statement in its deliberations.</t>
													</para.text>
												</para>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="no">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Alternatively, the judge could admit the
															conditionally relevant
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">evidence only after the introduction of the
															evidence sufficient to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">support a finding of the condition. Before the
															judge admits the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">conditionally relevant evidence, he will first
															decide whether a
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">reasonable jury could conclude that the
															condition has been met.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">If the judge determines that a reasonable jury
															could not so
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">conclude, the jury will not hear the
															conditionally relevant
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">evidence. If the judge determines that a
															reasonable jury could
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">find that the condition was met, he will allow
															the jury to hear the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">conditionally relevant evidence. The judge may
															also instruct the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">jury that, if it concludes that the condition
															was not met by a
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">preponderance of the evidence, it must
															disregard the condition
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ally relevant evidence. In the above example,
															if the judge, after
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">hearing evidence of the spoken statement,
															determines that a rea
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">sonable jury could not conclude that X heard
															the statement, he
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">will not allow the jury to hear the contents of
															the spoken
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">statement. However, if the judge determines
															that a reasonable
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">jury could conclude that X heard the statement,
															the judge will al
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">low the jury to hear the contents of the
															statement. The jury will
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">then decide whether X in fact heard the
															statement.
														</t>
													</para.text>
												</para>
											</editorial.commentary>
										</primary.features>
									</primary.section.body>
								</primary.section>
								<pagebreak num="16" num-string="16" prev_page="15"/>
								<primary.section primary.section.type="article" uuid="I43a387d0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" pgwidth="broad" date.revised="0" date.updated="0" element1="designator" prefix1="Art." suffix1=".">
									<sectionbreak sectionuuid="I45a3bde1eac711d8b93285946e571caf"/><XPPMetaData uuid="I43a387d0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" guid="I3ce35f3202ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.uuid="I3ce35f3202ae11da9c03bd72365340b3" md.dmsserial="296365758" md.first_line_cite="LAPRAC&amp;ndash;EVID ART. 105" md.pubpage="ART. 105" md.second_line_cite="La. Prac. Evidence Art. 105 (2017 ed.)" md.normalizedcite="LAPRAC-EVIDART.105" md.doc_family_uuid="I45a3bde1eac711d8b93285946e571caf" md.third_line_cite="" md.pubid="165245" name="Art 105. Limited admissibility" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art
										105.
										Limited admissibility
									</XPPMetaData>
									<XPPHier uuid="I43a387d0d68211e3a4e491f0ab88f383" name="Art 105. Limited admissibility" parent_uuid="I39cb32a0a5fc11d9b0c7867999d61bde">Art 105.
										Limited admissibility
									</XPPHier>
									<primary.section.front date.updated="0">
										<primary.outline.name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0" all.align="l" all.designator.suffix="." all.label.suffix="." all.element.group="all" all.style="block" all.indent="0" all.capitalization="asis" all.name.block.font.size="11" all.date.updated="0">
											<label date.updated="0">
												<t style="label.1">Art</t>
											</label>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<designator date.updated="0">
												<t style="designator">105</t>
											</designator>
											<t style="primary.outline.name.block cgt">. </t>
											<primary.name date.updated="0">
												<name date.updated="0">
													<t style="name">Limited admissibility</t>
												</name>
												<t style="primary.name">
												</t>
											</primary.name>
										</primary.outline.name.block>
									</primary.section.front>
									<primary.section.body date.updated="0">
										<primary.official.content date.updated="0">
											<stat.subsect uuid="Ief99e8502b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" sameline="no" date.updated="0">
												<stat.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
													<t style="stat.text">When evidence which is admissible as to one
														party or for one
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">purpose but not admissible as to another party
														or for another
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">purpose is admitted, the court, upon request,
														shall restrict the
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">evidence to its proper scope and instruct the
														jury accordingly.
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">Failure to restrict the evidence and instruct
														the jury shall not
													</t>
													<t style="stat.text">constitute error absent a request to do so.</t>
												</stat.text>
											</stat.subsect>
										</primary.official.content>
										<primary.features date.updated="0">
											<official.commentary uuid="Ief9c0b302b3d11e7b6a3d85239113e25" date.updated="0">
												<primary.head align="c" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold">LEGISLATIVE COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
													</name.block>
												</primary.head>
												<primary.para date.updated="0">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text">This Article differs somewhat from </t>
														<cite>
															<ref normalpub="judicial-us-revid" ref.id="Id2f4c020241411e68b798696bfab1886" ruleref="105">
																<t style="ref">Federal Rule of Evidence 105</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">. Although </t>
														<t style="para.text">generally it follows prior Louisiana law, see
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref case.id="1978139212" court="La. Ct. App. 2d Cir." date="1978" fjur="La" jur="La" norm.rptr="so2d" p1="Freeman" p2="Bell" post.rptr="197" pre.rptr="366" ref.id="Id2f4c021241411e68b798696bfab1886" title="Freeman v. Bell">
																<t style="ref">Freeman v. Bell, 366 So. 2d 197 </t>
																<t style="ref">(La. Ct. App. 2d Cir. 1978)</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">, in civil cases this Article makes mandatory a
															class
														</t>
														<t style="para.text">of instructions that were formerly
															discretionary under
														</t>
														<cite>
															<ref artref="1792" normalpub="statute-us-la-cdcivp" ref.id="Id2f4c022241411e68b798696bfab1886" subref="(A)">
																<t style="ref">Article 1792(A) of the La. </t>
																<t style="ref">Code of Civil Procedure</t>
															</ref>
														</cite>
														<t style="para.text">.</t>
													</para.text>
												</primary.para>
											</official.commentary>
											<editorial.commentary date.updated="0">
												<head align="c" toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
													<name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0">
														<name date.updated="0">
															<t style="bold.1">AUTHORS' COMMENTS</t>
														</name>
														<t style="name.block cgt">
														</t>
													</name.block>
												</head>
												<para date.updated="0" first.para="yes">
													<para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes">
														<t style="para.text.1">Recognizing that evidence may be admissible for
															one purpose
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">and not for another or as to one party and not
															as to another, this
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">Article directs the trial judge, upon request,
															to admit the evi
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">dence for such purpose or as to such party with
															a limiting instruc
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">tion to the jury that restricts the scope and
															purpose of the
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">evidence. The Article also states that failure
															of the trial judge to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">restrict the evidence and instruct the jury
															shall not constitute er
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">ror absent a request to do so.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">1</t>
														<xref id="40" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> On the other hand, the failure of </t>
														<t style="para.text.1">the trial judge to give a limiting instruction,
															upon request, consti
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">tutes error.</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">2</t>
														<xref id="41" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1"> Moreover, in a criminal case, if a limiting
															instruction
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">is desired, it is defense counsel's
															responsibility to request one.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">3</t>
														<xref id="42" type="footnote"/>
														<t style="para.text.1">
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">Because a jury is not present in a bench trial,
															this article does
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">not apply in such a trial as the trial judge is
															presumed to
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.1">understand what evidence is admissible and for
															what purposes.
														</t>
														<t style="para.text.2 super cgt">4</t>
														<xref id="43" type="footnote"/>
													</para.text>
												</para>
											</editorial.commentary>
										</primary.features>
									</primary.section.body>
								</primary.section>
